<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-the-chain-rule">
	<title>The Chain Rule</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			In this section, we discuss the higher dimension analogue of the <em>chain rule</em> from single variable calculus.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection>
		<title>Composite functions</title>

		<definition>
			<title>Composite Function</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					If <m>\mathbf{g} : \R^n \to \R^p</m> and <m>\mathbf{f} : \R^p \to \R^m</m> are multivariable functions, we can form a new <term>composite function</term> as follows.
					Take an input in <m>\R^n</m>, and then apply <m>\mathbf{g}</m> to the input to obtain a vector in <m>\R^p</m>. Apply <m>\mathbf{f}</m> to this vector to obtain a vector <m>\R^m</m>. This is the output of the composite function. In other words, out input is fed through the following diagram
					<me>\R^n \xrightarrow{\mathbf{g}} \R^p \xrightarrow{\mathbf{f}} \R^m</me>.
					We write the composite function as <m>\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g}</m> (the symbol <m>\circ</m> should be read as <q>composed with</q>). In symbols, the composite function is defined as
					<me>
						(\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g})(\mathbf{x}) = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x}))
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<remark>
			<p>
				Note that the composite <m>\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g}</m> is <em>only</em> defined when the output of <m>\mathbf{g}</m> is a possible input to <m>\mathbf{f}</m>, i.e. the output of <m>\mathbf{g}</m> is <m>\R^p</m>, which is the space of inputs to <m>\mathbf{f}</m>.
			</p>
		</remark>

		<p>
			Note that we have already encounted the composition of linear transformations in <xref ref="act-3-3-composition-matrix"/>. Here is another exercise of that type as a reminder. 
		</p>

		<activity>
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Let <m>\mathbf{T}_1: \R^2 \to \R^3</m> and <m>\mathbf{T}_2: \R^3 \to \R^2</m> be linear transformations defined by their component functions as follows:
					<me>
						\mathbf{T}_1(x,y) = (2x-y,3y,x+y) \qquad
						\mathbf{T}_2(u,v,w) = (y + v - w, 2u - v)
					</me>.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the matrices <m>A_1</m> and <m>A_2</m> associated with these transformations, so that <m>\mathbf{T}_1 = T_{A_1}</m> and <m>\mathbf{T}_2 = T_{A_2}</m> (recall the notation from <xref ref="def-3-2-matrix-transformation"/>).
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We recall the method of <xref ref="thm-linear-transformation-matrix"/>. In particular, we obtain the first column of <m>A_1</m> from the entries of <m>\mathbf{T}_1(\mathbf{e}_1)</m>, and the second column from <m>\mathbf{T}_1(\mathbf{e}_2)</m>. We calculate that
						<me>
							\mathbf{T}_1(\mathbf{e}_1) = \mathbf{T}_1(1,0) = (2 \cdot 1 - 0, 3 \cdot 0, 1 + 0) = (2, 0, 1)
						</me>
						and that
						<me>
							\mathbf{T}_2(\mathbf{e}_2) = \mathbf{T}_2(0,1) = (2 \cdot 0 - 1, 3 \cdot 1, 0 + 1) = (-1, 3, 1)
						</me>.
						So the matrix <m>A_1</m> is equal to
						<me>
							A_1 = \begin{pmatrix}
							2 \amp -1 \\
							0 \amp 3 \\
							1 \amp 1
							\end{pmatrix}
						</me>.
					</p>

					<p>
						Similarily, we calculate that
						<me>\mathbf{T}_2(\mathbf{e}_1) = \mathbf{T}_2(1,0,0) = (1 + 0 - 0, 2 \cdot 1 - 0) = (1, 2)</me>,
						that
						<me>\mathbf{T}_2(\mathbf{e}_2) = \mathbf{T}_2(0,1,0) = (0 + 1 - 0, 2 \cdot 0 - 1) = (1, -1)</me>,
						and that
						<me>\mathbf{T}_2(\mathbf{e}_3) = \mathbf{T}_2(0,0,1) = (0 + 0 - 1, 2 \cdot 0 - 0) = (-1, 0)</me>.
						So the matrix <m>A_2</m> is given by
						<me>
							A_2 = \begin{pmatrix}
							1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
							2 \amp -1 \amp 0
							\end{pmatrix}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</task>
			<task>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Calculate the composite transformation <m>\mathbf{T}_2 \circ \mathbf{T}_1</m> and express it as a matrix transformation from <m>\R^2</m> to <m>\R^2</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						Recalling <xref ref="act-3-3-composition-matrix"/>, we have that <m>\mathbf{T}_2 \circ \mathbf{T}_1 = T_{A_2 A_1}</m>. Now

						<md>
							<mrow>
								A_2 \cdot A_1 \amp= \begin{pmatrix}
								1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \\
								2 \amp -1 \amp 0
								\end{pmatrix}
								\begin{pmatrix}
								2 \amp -1 \\
								0 \amp 3 \\
								1 \amp 1
								\end{pmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= \begin{pmatrix}
								1 \cdot 2 + 1 \cdot 0 + (-1) \cdot 1 \amp 1 \cdot (-1) + 1 \cdot 3 + (-1) \cdot 1 \\
								2 \cdot 2 + (-1) \cdot 0 + 0 \cdot 1 \amp 2 \cdot (-1) + (-1) \cdot 3 + 0 \cdot 1
								\end{pmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= \begin{pmatrix}
								2 + 0 - 1 \amp -1 + 3 - 1 \\
								4 + 0 + 0 \amp -2 - 3 + 0
								\end{pmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= \begin{pmatrix}
								1 \amp 1 \\
								4 \amp -5
								\end{pmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>

						Therefore, the composite transformation <m>\mathbf{T}_2 \circ \mathbf{T}_1: \R^2 \to \R^2</m> can be expressed as:

						<me>(\mathbf{T}_2 \circ \mathbf{T}_1) \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}
							1 \amp 1 \\
							4 \amp -5
							\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} = (x + y, 4x - 5y)</me>
						</p>
					</solution>
				</task>
			</activity>

			<p>
				Here is a nonlinear example of the composition of two functions.
			</p>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Consider <m>\mathbf{f} : \R^2 \to \R^2</m> and <m>\mathbf{g} : \R^2 \to \R^2</m> defined by
						<me>
							\mathbf{f}(u, v) = (uv, u + v) \quad\text{and}\quad \mathbf{g}(x, y) = (e^{xy}, x - y)
						</me>.
						Find expressions for <m>(\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g})(x, y)</m> and <m>(\mathbf{g} \circ \mathbf{f})(u, v)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We calculate that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								(\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g})(x, y) \amp= \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{g}(x, y))
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= \mathbf{f}(e^{xy}, x - y)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= (e^{xy}(x - y), e^{xy} + (x - y))
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= (e^{xy}x - e^{xy}y, e^{xy} + x - y)
							</mrow>
						</md>,
						and that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								(\mathbf{g} \circ \mathbf{f})(u, v) \amp= \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{f}(u, v))
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= \mathbf{g}(uv, u + v)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= (e^{uv(u+v)}, uv - (u + v))
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= (e^{u^2v + uv^2}, uv - u - v)
							</mrow>
						</md>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

			<warning>
				<p>
					Observe that <m>\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g}</m> and <m>\mathbf{g} \circ \mathbf{f}</m> are very different functions. We must therefore be careful that we compose functions in the correct order.
				</p>
			</warning>

			<activity>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Consider <m>\mathbf{r} : \R \to \R^3</m> and <m>\mathbf{p} : \R^3 \to \R^2</m> defined by
						<me>\mathbf{r}(t) = (t, \cos(t), \sin(t)) \quad\text{and}\quad \mathbf{p}(x, y, z) = (y, z)</me>
					</p>
				</introduction>

				<task>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Find an expression for <m>(\mathbf{p} \circ \mathbf{r})(t)</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<solution>
						<p>
							We calculate that
							<md>
								<mrow>
									(\mathbf{p} \circ \mathbf{r})(t) \amp= \mathbf{p}(\mathbf{r}(t))
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= \mathbf{p}(t, \cos(t), \sin(t))
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= (\cos(t), \sin(t))
								</mrow>
							</md>.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</task>

				<task>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Is the composition <m>\mathbf{r} \circ \mathbf{p}</m> defined? Why or why not?
						</p>
					</statement>

					<solution>
						<p>
							For the composition <m>\mathbf{r} \circ \mathbf{p}</m> to be defined, the outputs of <m>\mathbf{p}</m> must be contained in the inputs of <m>\mathbf{r}</m>. But <m>\mathbf{p}</m> outputs points in <m>\R^2</m>, whereas <m>\mathbf{r}</m> takes in points in <m>\R</m> as input, so the composition does not make sense.
						</p>
					</solution>
				</task>
			</activity>

			<remark>
				<p>
					Compositions of vector-valued functions play a key role in modern machine learning. The figures below illustrate how deep neural networks are composite functions.
				</p>
			</remark>

		</subsection>

		<subsection>
			<title>Chain Rule Case 1: One Independent Variable</title>

			<p>
				Recall the chain rule from single-variable calculus, that for two functions <m>f: \R \to \R</m> and <m>g: \R \to \R</m>, we have
				<me>
					(f \circ g)'(t) = (f' \circ g)(t) g'(t)
				</me>.
				In this section we will give several generalizations of this rule to several vairables.
			</p>

			<p>
				Recall that for a function <m>f(x,y)</m>, <m>D_1 f = f_x = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}</m>, and that <m>D_2 f = f_y = \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}</m>.
			</p>

			<theorem xml:id="sec-9-2-chain-rule-1">
				<title>Chain Rule for One Independent Variable</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Consider a scalar-valued function <m>f: \R^2 \to \R</m>, and a vector-valued function <m>\mathbf{r}: \R \to \R^2</m> of a single variable. Then the composition <m>f \circ \mathbf{r}: \R \to \R</m> is a scalar-valued function of a single variable. If <m>\mathbf{r}</m> is differentiable at <m>t_0</m>, and <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>\mathbf{r}(t_0)</m>, then <m>f \circ \mathbf{r}</m> is differentiable at <m>t_0</m> and
						<me>
							(f \circ \mathbf{r})'(t_0) = (D_1 f \circ \mathbf{r})(t_0) r_1'(t_0) + (D_2 f \circ \mathbf{r})(t_0) r_2(t_0)
						</me>,
						where <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are the components of <m>\mathbf{r}</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<proof>
					<p>
						We note that the right hand side of the equation can be written as <m>L \circ \mathbf{r} - f(\mathbf{r}(t_0))</m>, where <m>L</m> is the linear approximation of <m>f</m> at <m>\mathbf{r}(t_0)</m>. Because <m>f</m> is differentiable, we know that
						<me>
							\lim_{\mathbf{x} \to \mathbf{r}(t_0)} \frac{f(\mathbf{x}) - L(\mathbf{x})}{\| \mathbf{x} - \mathbf{r}(t_0) \|} = 0
						</me>.
						Now
						<me>
							\lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{\| \mathbf{r}(t) - \mathbf{r}(t_0) \|}{t - t_0} = \left\| \lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{\mathbf{r}(t) - \mathbf{r}(t_0)}{t - t_0} \right\| = \| \mathbf{r}'(t_0) \|
						</me>.
						Using these two equations (substituting <m>\mathbf{r}(t)</m> for <m>\mathbf{x}</m> in the first equation), we find that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{f(\mathbf{r}(t)) - L(\mathbf{r}(t))}{t - t_0} \amp = \lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{f(\mathbf{r}(t)) - L(\mathbf{r}(t))}{\| \mathbf{r}(t) - \mathbf{r}(t_0) \|} \frac{\| \mathbf{r}(t) - \mathbf{r}(t_0) \|}{t - t_0}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = 0 \cdot \| \mathbf{r}'(t_0) \| = 0
							</mrow>
						</md>.
						But recalling that
						<me>L(x,y) = f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) + D_1 f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) (x - r_1(t_0)) + D_2 f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) (y - r_2(t_0))</me>,
						we conclude that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{f(\mathbf{r}(t)) - f(\mathbf{r}(t_0))}{t - t_0} \amp = \lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{f(\mathbf{r}(t)) - f(\mathbf{r}(t_0))}{t - t_0} - \frac{f(\mathbf{r}(t)) - L(\mathbf{r}(t))}{t - t_0}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \lim_{t \to t_0} \frac{L(\mathbf{r}(t)) - f(\mathbf{r}(t_0))}{t - t_0}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \lim_{t \to t_0} D_1 f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) \frac{r_1(t) - r_1(t_0)}{t - t_0}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp \quad\quad + D_2 f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) \frac{r_2(t) - r_2(t_0)}{t - t_0}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = f_x(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) r_1'(t_0) + D_2 f(\mathbf{r}(t_0)) r_2'(t_0)
							</mrow>
						</md>.
					</p>
				</proof>
			</theorem>

			<remark>
				<p>
					There are several ways to aid in remembering the formula for the chain rule. The first is to simplify the equation, writing it as
					<me>
						(f \circ \mathbf{r})'(t) = (\nabla f \circ \mathbf{r})(t) \cdot \mathbf{r}'(t),
					</me>
					so that the equation looks more like the chain rule from single variable calculus. The second is the following mnemonic: if we write <m>z</m> for <m>f \circ \mathbf{r}</m> and for <m>f</m>, and write the components of <m>\mathbf{r}</m> as <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, then the chain rule reads that
					<me>
						\frac{dz}{dt} = \frac{\partial z}{\partial x} \frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial y} \frac{dy}{dt}
					</me>,
					so that the symbols <m>dx</m> and <m>dy</m> in the numerators on the right hand side, and the symbols <m>\partial x</m> and <m>\partial y</m> that occur in the denominators appear to <sq>cancel</sq> like when multiplying fractions.
				</p>
			</remark>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose <m>z = x^2y - y^2x</m>, where <m>x = \sin t</m> and <m>y = e^t</m>. Compute <m>dz/dt</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						First, we need to calculate 
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} \amp= \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(x^2y - y^2x) = 2xy - y^2
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} \amp= \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(x^2y - y^2x) = x^2 - 2yx
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dx}{dt} \amp= \frac{d}{dt}(\sin t) = \cos t
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dy}{dt} \amp= \frac{d}{dt}(e^t) = e^t
							</mrow>
						</md>
						Now we substitute these into the chain rule formula:
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dz}{dt} \amp= (2xy - y^2) \cdot \cos t + (x^2 - 2yx) \cdot e^t
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= (2 \sin t \cdot e^t - e^{2t}) \cdot \cos t + (\sin^2 t - 2e^t \cdot \sin t) \cdot e^t
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= 2 \sin t \cdot e^t \cdot \cos t - e^{2t} \cdot \cos t + e^t \sin^2 t - 2e^{2t} \sin t
							</mrow>
						</md>
						We can simplify this further if we want:
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dz}{dt} \amp= 2 e^t \sin t \cos t - e^{2t} \cos t + e^t \sin^2 t - 2e^{2t} \sin t
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= e^t (\sin^2 t + 2\sin t \cos t) - e^{2t}(\cos t + 2\sin t)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp= e^t (\sin^2 t + \sin 2t) - e^{2t}(\cos t + 2\sin t)
							</mrow>
						</md>
						Therefore, 
						<me>
							\frac{dz}{dt} = e^t (\sin^2 t + \sin 2t) - e^{2t}(\cos t + 2\sin t)
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If <m>f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2</m>, and <m>\mathbf{r}(t) = (\sin t, \cos(2t))</m>, find <m>(f \circ \mathbf{r})'(t)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We calculate that 
						<me>
							\nabla f(x,y) = (2x,2y)
						</me>
						and that
						<me>
							\mathbf{r}'(t) = ( \cos t, - 2 \sin(2t) )
						</me>.
						Now
						<me>
							\nabla f \circ \mathbf{r}(t) = \nabla f(\sin t, \cos(2t)) = (2 \sin t, 2 \cos(2t))
						</me>
						Thus
						<md>
							<mrow>
								(f \circ \mathbf{r})'(t) \amp = \nabla f(\mathbf{r}(t)) \cdot \mathbf{r}'(t)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = (2 \sin t, 2 \cos(2t)) \cdot (\cos t, -2 \sin(2t))
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = 2 \sin t \cos t - 4 \sin(2t) \cos(2t)
							</mrow>
						</md>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>
		</subsection>

		<subsection>
			<title>Chain Rule Case 2: Two Independent Variables</title>

			<theorem xml:id="thm-chain-rule-2">
				<title>Chain Rule for Two Independent Variables</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose <m>f: \R^2 \to \R</m> is a scalar-valued function, and <m>\mathbf{g}: \R^2 \to \R^2</m> is a vector-valued function. Then <m>f \circ \mathbf{g}: \R^2 \to \R</m> is a scalar-valued function, and the two equations
						<me>
							D_1(f \circ \mathbf{g}) = (D_1 f \circ \mathbf{g}) D_1 g_1 + (D_2 f \circ \mathbf{g}) D_1 g_2
						</me>
						and
						<me>
							D_2(f \circ \mathbf{g}) = (D_1 f \circ \mathbf{g}) D_2 g_1 + (D_2 f \circ \mathbf{g}) D_2 g_2
						</me>
						hold.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<proof>
					<p>
						Fix the second variable, and apply <xref ref="sec-9-2-chain-rule-1"/> to the first to obtain the formula for <m>(f \circ g)_x</m>. Then fix the first variable and apply <xref ref="sec-9-2-chain-rule-1"/> to the second variable to obtain the formula for <m>(f \circ g)_y</m>.
					</p>
				</proof>
			</theorem>

			<remark>
				<p>
					As with the first chain rule, there are several ways to memorize this chain rule. The first is to consider the <em>Jacobian matrix</em>
					<me>
						J_{\mathbf{g}} = \begin{pmatrix} D_1 g_1 \amp D_2 g_1 \\ D_1 g_2 \amp D_2 g_2 \end{pmatrix}
					</me>.
					Then we can write the pair of equations in <xref ref="thm-chain-rule-2"/> as the single vector equation
					<me>
						\nabla (f \circ \mathbf{g}) = J_\mathbf{g}^T (\nabla f \circ \mathbf{g})
					</me>,
					where we interpret <m>\nabla f</m> as a column vector.
				</p>

				<p>
					The second method is mnemonic. If we let <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> be the variables of <m>f</m>, and <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> be the variables of <m>g</m>, and we write <m>z</m> for <m>f \circ \mathbf{g}</m> and for <m>f</m>, and write the components of <m>\mathbf{g}(u,v)</m> as <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, then the chain rule reads that
					<me>
						\frac{\partial f}{\partial u} = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial u} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial u}
					</me>
					and that
					<me>
						\frac{\partial f}{\partial v} = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial v} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial v}
					</me>,
					so that the partials in the numerator and denominator again appear to <sq>cancel</sq>.
				</p>
			</remark>

			<activity>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Suppose that
						<me>
							z = x^2 + xy - y^2
						</me>
						that <m>x = e^{2s + t}</m>, and that <m>y = \ln(t/2)</m>. Compute
						<me>
							\frac{\partial z}{\partial s} \quad\text{and}\quad \frac{\partial z}{\partial t}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</introduction>

				<task>
					<statement>
						<p>
							First compute the partial derivatives of <m>z</m> in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, and the partial derivatives of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in <m>t</m> and <m>s</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<solution>
						<p>
							We calculate that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}(x^2 + xy - y^2) = 2x + y
							</me>,
							that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} = \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(x^2 + xy - y^2) = x - 2y
							</me>,
							that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial x}{\partial s} = \frac{\partial}{\partial s}(e^{2s+t}) = 2e^{2s+t}
							</me>,
							that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial x}{\partial t} = \frac{\partial}{\partial t}(e^{2s+t}) = e^{2s+t}
							</me>,
							that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial y}{\partial s} = \frac{\partial}{\partial s}\left(\ln\left(\frac{t}{s}\right)\right) = \frac{\partial}{\partial s}(\ln(t) - \ln(s)) = -\frac{1}{s}
							</me>,
							and that
							<me>
								\frac{\partial y}{\partial t} = \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\ln\left(\frac{t}{s}\right)\right) = \frac{1}{t}
							</me>
						</p>
					</solution>
				</task>

				<task>
					<statement>
						<p>
							Now use the chain rule to compute the partial derivatives of <m>z</m> in <m>s</m> and <m>t</m>.
						</p>
					</statement>

					<solution>
						<p>
							Now we apply the chain rule, from which we conclude that
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\frac{\partial z}{\partial s} \amp= \frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\frac{\partial x}{\partial s} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\frac{\partial y}{\partial s}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= (2x + y) \cdot 2e^{2s+t} + (x - 2y) \cdot (-1/s)
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= 4xe^{2s+t} + 2ye^{2s+t} - (x/2) + (2y/s)
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Substituting <m>x = e^{2s+t}</m> and <m>y = \ln(t/s)</m>:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\frac{\partial z}{\partial s} \amp= 4e^{2s+t} \cdot e^{2s+t} + 2 \ln(t/s) \cdot e^{2s+t} - \frac{e^{2s+t}}{s} + \frac{2\ln(t/s)}{s}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= 4e^{4s+2t} + 2e^{2s+t}\ln(t/s) - \frac{e^{2s+t}}{s} + \frac{2\ln(t/s)}{s}
								</mrow>
							</md>

							Similarly for <m>\frac{\partial z}{\partial t}</m>:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\frac{\partial z}{\partial t} \amp= \frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\frac{\partial x}{\partial t} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\frac{\partial y}{\partial t}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= (2x + y) \cdot e^{2s+t} + (x - 2y) \cdot \frac{1}{t}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= 2xe^{2s+t} + ye^{2s+t} + \frac{x}{t} - \frac{2y}{t}
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Substituting <m>x = e^{2s+t}</m> and <m>y = \ln(t/s)</m>:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\frac{\partial z}{\partial t} \amp= 2e^{2s+t} \cdot e^{2s+t} + \ln(t/s) \cdot e^{2s+t} + \frac{e^{2s+t}}{t} - \frac{2\ln(t/s)}{t}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\amp= 2e^{4s+2t} + e^{2s+t}\ln(t/s) + \frac{e^{2s+t}}{t} - \frac{2\ln(t/s)}{t}
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
					</solution>
				</task>
			</activity>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Use the Jacobian matrix version of the chain rule to calculate the partial derivatives of the function <m>f \circ \mathbf{g}</m>, where <m>f(x,y) = 3x^2 - 2xy + y^2</m>, and <m>\mathbf{g}(x,y) = (3u + 2v, 4u - v)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We compute that
						<me>
							\nabla f(x,y) = ( 6x - 2y, -2x + 2y )
						</me>
						and that
						<me>
							J_{\mathbf{g}} = \begin{pmatrix} D_1 \{ 3u + 2v \} \amp D_2 \{ 3u + 2v \} \\ D_1 \{ 4u - v \} \amp D_2 \{ 4u - v \} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 4 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix}
						</me>
						Since
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\nabla f(3u + 2v, 4u - v) \amp = ( 6(3u + 2v) - 2 (4u - v), -2(3u + 2v) + 2(4u - v) )
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = ( 10u + 14v, 2u - 6v )
							</mrow>
						</md>,
						we find that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\nabla (f \circ \mathbf{g}) \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 4 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}^T \begin{bmatrix} 10u + 14v \\ 2u - 6v \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 4 \\ 2 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 10 u + 14v \\ 2u - 6v \end{bmatrix} 
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} (3)(10u + 14v) + (4)(2u - 6v) \\ (2)(10u + 14v) + (-1) (2u - 6v) \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 38u + 18v \\ 18u + 34v \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

		</subsection>

		<subsection>
			<title>The Generalized Chain Rule</title>

			<p>
				Now we obtain a generalize chain rule for the composition of functions of arbitrarily many variables.
			</p>

			<definition>
				<title>Jacobian Matrix</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						For a vector-valued function <m>\mathbf{f}: \R^n \to \R^m</m> given by 
						<me>
							\mathbf{f}(\mathbf{x}) = (f_1(\mathbf{x}), f_2(\mathbf{x}), \ldots, f_m(\mathbf{x}))
						</me> 
						where <m>\mathbf{x} = (x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n)</m>, the <term>Jacobian matrix</term> of <m>\mathbf{f}</m> is the <m>m \times n</m> matrix:

						<me>
							J_{\mathbf{f}}(\mathbf{x}) = 
							\begin{pmatrix}
							\frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_1} \amp \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_2} \amp \ldots \amp \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_n} \\
							\frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_1} \amp \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_2} \amp \ldots \amp \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_n} \\
							\vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
							\frac{\partial f_m}{\partial x_1} \amp \frac{\partial f_m}{\partial x_2} \amp \ldots \amp \frac{\partial f_m}{\partial x_n}
							\end{pmatrix}
						</me>
					</p>
				</statement>
			</definition>

			<theorem>
				<title>Generalized Chain Rule</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose <m>\mathbf{f}: \R^p \to \R^m</m> and <m>\mathbf{g}: \R^n \to \R^p</m> are differentiable functions. Then <m>\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g}: \R^n \to \R^m</m> is differentiable, and
						<me>
							J_{\mathbf{f} \circ \mathbf{g}}(\mathbf{x}) = J_{\mathbf{f}}(\mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x})) J_{\mathbf{g}}(\mathbf{x})
						</me>,
						where the right hand side is defined by matrix multiplications. Equivalently, for <m>1 \leq i \leq m</m>,
						<me>
							D_j \{ f_i \circ \mathbf{g} \}(\mathbf{x}) = \sum_{k = 1}^p (D_k f_i)(\mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x})) (D_j \mathbf{g}_k)(\mathbf{x})
						</me>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</theorem>

			<remark>
				<p>
					If <m>f</m> is a scalar valued function, then the generalized chain rule tells us that
					<me>
						\nabla (f \circ \mathbf{g}) = J_{\mathbf{g}}^T (\nabla f \circ \mathbf{g})
					</me>
					as in the two variable case.
				</p>
			</remark>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose <m>f(x,y,z) = 3x^2 - 2xy + 4z^2</m>, and that <m>\mathbf{g}(x,y) = (e^u \sin v, e^u \cos v, e^u )</m>. Compute the partial derivatives of <m>f \circ \mathbf{g}</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We calculate that
						<me>
							\nabla f(x,y,z) = (6x - 2y, -2x, 8z)
						</me>
						so that
						<me>
							\nabla f(e^u \sin v, e^u \cos v, e^u) = e^u ( 6\sin v - 2 \cos v, -2 \sin v, 8 )
						</me>.
						Now
						<me>
							J_{\mathbf{g}}(u,v) = \begin{bmatrix} e^u \sin v \amp e^u \cos v \\ e^u \cos v \amp - e^u \sin v \\ e^u \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = e^u \begin{bmatrix} \sin v \amp \cos v \\ \cos v \amp - \sin v \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
						</me>.
						Thus
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\nabla (f \circ \mathbf{g})(u,v) \amp = J_{\mathbf{g}}(u,v)^T (\nabla f \circ \mathbf{g})(u,v)
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = (e^u)^2 \begin{bmatrix} \sin v \amp \cos v \amp 1 \\ \cos v \amp - \sin v \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 6 \sin v - 2 \cos v \\ -2 \sin v \\ 8 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = e^{2u} \begin{bmatrix} 6 (\sin v)^2 - 2 \sin v \cos v - 2 \sin v \cos v + 8 \\ 6 \sin v cos v - 2 (\cos v)^2 + 2 (\sin v)^2 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = e^{2u} \begin{bmatrix} 6 (\sin v)^2 - 4 \sin v \cos v + 8 \\ 4 (\sin v)^2 + 6 \sin v \cos v - 2 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>.
						From this calculation, we can read that the partial derivative of <m>f \circ \mathbf{g}</m> in the first variable is equal to
						<me>
							e^{2u} ( 6 (\sin v)^2 - 4 \sin v \cos v + 8 )
						</me>
						and the derivative in the second variable is
						<me>
							e^{2u} ( 4 (\sin v)^2 + 6 \sin v \cos v - 2 )
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

		</subsection>

		<subsection>
			<title>More on the Jacobian matrix</title>

			<p>
				The Jacobian matrix generalizes the concept of the derivative to a vector-valued function of multiple variables. It provides a compact representation of all first-order partial derivatives of a function.
			</p>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the Jacobian matrix of <m>f(x,y,z) = xy + yz + xz</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						For a scalar-valued function <m>f: \R^n \to \R</m>, the Jacobian is simply the gradient, i.e. <m>J_f = \nabla f^T</m>. So
						<me>
							J_f = \nabla f^T = \begin{bmatrix} y + z \amp x + z \amp x + y \end{bmatrix}
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute the Jacobian matrix of <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y) = ( x^2 - y^2, 2xy, x+y )</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We compute that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								J_{\mathbf{F}} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} D_1 F_1 \amp D_2 F_1 \\ D_1 F_2 \amp D_2 F_2 \\ D_1 F_3 \amp D_2 F_3 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2x \amp -2y \\ 2y \amp 2x \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Compute the Jacobian matrix of the gradient function <m>\nabla f(x,y)</m> for <m>f(x,y) = x^2 + xy + y^2</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						First, let's compute the gradient of <m>f(x,y) = x^2 + xy + y^2</m>:
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \amp= 2x + y
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \amp= x + 2y
							</mrow>
						</md>
						So <m>\nabla f(x,y) = ( 2x + y, x + 2y )</m>.
						The Jacobian of the gradient is
						<md>
							<mrow>
								J_{\nabla f} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} D_1 (\nabla f)_1 \amp D_2 (\nabla f)_1 \\ D_1 (\nabla f)_2 \amp D_2 (\nabla f)_2 \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} D_1 \{ 2x + y \} \amp D_2 \{ 2x + y \} \\ D_1 \{ x + 2y \} \amp D_2 \{ x + 2y \} \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							</mrow>
						</md>.
						Note that this is the <em>Hessian</em> of <m>f</m> (recall <xref ref="def-8-5-hessian"/>).
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

			<p>
				Just as the gradient can be used to obtain a linear approximation of a scalar-valued function <m>f</m>, we can use the Jacobian to obtain a linear approximation of a vector-valued function.
			</p>

			<definition>
				<title>Linear Approximation of Vector-Valued Functions</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>\mathbf{F}: \R^n \to \R^m</m> be a vector-valued function. Provided that the partial derivatives of the components of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> all exist at <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, so that the Jacobian <m>J_{\mathbf{F}}</m> is well-defind, the <term>linear approximation</term> of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> at <m>\mathbf{a}</m> is the vector-valued function
						<me>
							\mathbf{L}(\mathbf{x}) = 
							\mathbf{F}(\mathbf{a}) + J_{\mathbf{F}}(\mathbf{a})(\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{a})
						</me>
						where <m>J_{\mathbf{F}}(\mathbf{a}) (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{a})</m> is the Jacobian matrix of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> evaluated at <m>\mathbf{a}</m>, and then applied to the vector <m>\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{a}</m>.
					</p>

					<p>
						The components of <m>\mathbf{L}</m> are precisely the linear approximations of the components of <m>\mathbf{F}</m>, i.e. <m>L_i(\mathbf{x}) = F_i(\mathbf{a}) + (\nabla F_i)(\mathbf{a}) \cdot (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{a})</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</definition>

			<remark>
				<p>
					Geometrically, the graph of the linear approximation to a vector-valued function can be visualized as a higher dimensional <q>tangent plane</q> of the graph of the function <m>\mathbf{F}</m> at <m>\mathbf{a}</m>.
				</p>
			</remark>

			<remark>
				<p>
					The linear approximation of a vector-valued function occurs in many contexts in applications, such as in Newton's method for solving systems of nonlinear equations, in optimization algorithms, and in understanding how small changes in inputs affect the outputs of complex functions. The generalized chain rule plays a fundamental role in deep learning and neural networks through the backpropagation algorithm. In backpropagation, gradients of the loss function are propagated backward through the network using successive applications of the chain rule, allowing the network to learn through gradient-based optimization. The efficient computation of these gradients relies critically on the matrix formulation of the chain rule above.
				</p>
			</remark>

			<activity>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Let <m>\mathbf{F}(x,y) = ( x^2y, xe^y )</m>. Find the linear approximation of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> at the point <m>(1,0)</m>, and use it to approximate <m>\mathbf{F}(1.1, -0.2)</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<solution>
					<p>
						We compute that
						<md>
							<mrow>
								J_{\mathbf{F}} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \{ x^2 y \} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \{ x^2 y \} \\ \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \{ xe^y \} \amp \frac{\partial}{\partial y} \{ xe^y \} \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 2xy \amp x^2 \\ e^y \amp xe^y \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>.
						In particular,
						<me>
							J_{\mathbf{F}}(1,0) = \begin{bmatrix} 2(1)(0) \amp (1)^2 \\ e^{(0)} \amp (1)e^{(0)} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
						</me>.
						SInce
						<me>
							\mathbf{F}(1,0) = ( (1)^2(0), (1)e^{(0)} ) = (0,1)
						</me>.
						So the linear approximation of <m>\mathbf{F}</m> at <m>(1,0)</m> is the function
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\mathbf{L} \begin{bmatrix} x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} x - 1 \\ y \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1y \\ 1 + (x - 1) + y \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
							<mrow>
								\amp = \begin{bmatrix} y \\ x + y \end{bmatrix}
							</mrow>
						</md>.
						So
						<me>
							\mathbf{F}(1.1,-0.2) \approx \mathbf{L}(1.1,-0.2) = (-0.2, 1.1 - 0.2) = (-0.2,-0.9)
						</me>.
					</p>
				</solution>
			</activity>

		</subsection>

	</section>